<h2><a name="gets" id="gets">gets</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cstdio&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">char</span> <span class="sy0">*</span>gets<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">char</span> <span class="sy0">*</span>str <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;</pre>
<p>

The gets() function reads characters from stdin and loads them into str, until
a newline or <acronym title="End of file">EOF</acronym> is reached. The newline character is translated into a null
termination. The return value of gets() is the read-in string, or NULL if there
is an error.
Note that gets() does not perform bounds checking, and thus risks overrunning
str. For a similar (and safer) function that includes bounds checking, see
fgets().
</p>

<p>
Related Topics: <a href="fgetc" class="wikilink1" title="c:io:fgetc">fgetc</a>, <a href="fgets" class="wikilink1" title="c:io:fgets">fgets</a>, <a href="fputs" class="wikilink1" title="c:io:fputs">fputs</a>, <a href="puts" class="wikilink1" title="c:io:puts">puts</a>
</p>

